;; 07-where-to-write-log.book.slatl
;; Book of Systems — Chapter 7

(chapter
  :book             "Book of Systems"
  :chapter-number   7
  :title            "Where To Write Log"
  :audience         "Motoi Copilot + Motoi engineers"
  :dialect          "motoi"
  :date             "2026-07-16"
  :status           "authored, first pass"
  :prose
"Logs are what the Copilot writes so a person can look later. A
crash trace. A note that a cortex read missed. A record that a
verb was called with an unexpected shape. Logs are for humans —
usually the engineer, sometimes the user, sometimes the Copilot
itself when it is trying to explain a decision.

The rule: **logs go in a bounded file, in a directory the user or
engineer can find.** Bounded, because logs that grow forever
become the disk problem they were supposed to help diagnose.
Findable, because a log that a person cannot open is not a log.

Per host:

- `phone-ios`, `tablet-ipad`:
  A `logs/` subdirectory of the data directory. The Copilot
  keeps one active file, `motoi.log`, and rotates it when it
  reaches the size cap. The user can retrieve it through the
  Files app if `UIFileSharingEnabled`; otherwise the engineer
  reads it via a diagnostic export the host provides.

- `phone-android`, `tablet-android`:
  A `logs/` subdirectory of the app's files area. Same pattern.

- `computer-macos`:
  `~/Library/Logs/<AppName>/motoi.log`. macOS has a dedicated
  Logs tree; Console.app will surface these files.

- `computer-linux`:
  `${XDG_STATE_HOME:-~/.local/state}/<AppName>/logs/motoi.log`.
  XDG's state tree is the honest home for logs — not cache
  (which the OS may evict), not data (which the OS backs up).

- `computer-windows`:
  `%LOCALAPPDATA%\\<AppName>\\Logs\\motoi.log`. Local, not
  Roaming — logs should not sync across profiles.

- `unknown`:
  `./motoi-data/logs/motoi.log`.

Read pattern:

```scheme
(define (motoi/log-dir)
  (or (get-environment-variable \"MOTOI_LOG_DIR\")
      (string-append (motoi/data-dir) \"/logs\")))

(define (motoi/log-path)
  (string-append (motoi/log-dir) \"/motoi.log\"))
```

The size cap defaults to 5 MB per file, and the Copilot keeps
the last three rotated files: `motoi.log`, `motoi.log.1`,
`motoi.log.2`. On rotation, the oldest is dropped. That is a
total of 15 MB of log on disk — enough to reconstruct the last
several sessions, small enough to fit anywhere.

The log format is SLAT — one record per line, each record a
proper Scheme datum the Copilot itself could read back. This
matters because the log doubles as a replay source when
diagnosing a bug: the engineer can point a debug session at an
old log and step through what the Copilot did.

```scheme
;; A single log record — one line, one datum.
(log :time \"2026-07-16T14:22:03Z\"
     :level info
     :where cortex/recall
     :note \"miss on key 'operator-timezone'\")
```

What must not go in the log:

- User-typed secrets (there are none, but if a future adapter
  ever handles them, they must not be logged).
- Verbatim large user data. Log the summary shape, not the
  contents. \"Loaded 231-record cortex\" is a log line; the
  231 records are not.
- Any personally identifying information beyond what the user
  stored themselves and is already visible to whoever holds
  the device.

The Copilot writes to log through a single helper. That helper
knows the size cap, knows the rotation, and refuses to be
bypassed. Freeform writes elsewhere are not logs; they are just
files.")
